  "prompt": "How are septums pierced?",
  "response": "A septum piercing is done through the thin bit of cartilage and skin just inside the tip of your nose, often called the \"sweet spot.\" Here's a breakdown of the process:\n\n1.  **Consultation and Marking:**\n    *   The piercer will first talk to you about placement, jewelry options, and aftercare.\n    *   They'll examine your septum to find the \"sweet spot,\" which is ideally a thin, fleshy area of tissue, not cartilage.\n    *   They'll mark the spot with a surgical marker to ensure the piercing is centered and symmetrical.\n\n2.  **Preparation:**\n    *   The piercer will wash their hands, put on gloves, and disinfect the area inside and outside your nose with an antiseptic solution.\n    *   They'll then use sterilized tools.\n    *   **Sterilization is essential** to prevent infection.\n\n3.  **Clamping:**\n    *   The piercer uses sterilized clamps, often called septum forceps, to hold the tissue in place and stabilize it. These clamps also help guide the needle.\n    *   The clamps may be a bit uncomfortable but are crucial for accurate piercing.\n\n4.  **Piercing:**\n    *   The piercer uses a sterile, hollow piercing needle (typically a 16G or 14G) to pierce through the marked spot.\n    *   This is usually a quick process, though you'll feel some pressure and a sharp pinch.\n    *   The needle should go through the soft tissue, not cartilage, for the piercing to heal properly.\n\n5.  **Jewelry Insertion:**\n    *   Immediately after the needle goes through, the piercer inserts the jewelry. Common choices for initial jewelry include:\n        *   **Circular barbell (horseshoe):** This is very common and easily flipped up into the nostrils if needed.\n        *   **Captive bead ring (CBR):** A ring with a bead held in place by tension.\n        *   **Retainer:** A staple-shaped piece that can be flipped up easily to hide the piercing.\n    *   The jewelry is also sterile.\n\n6.  **Final Steps:**\n    *   The piercer will remove the clamps.\n    *   They will clean the area again.\n    *   They will give you detailed aftercare instructions.\n\n**Important considerations:**\n\n*   **Choosing a reputable piercer:**  Look for a piercer who is licensed (where applicable), experienced, and works in a clean, professional studio.  Check reviews and ask for recommendations. A good piercer will prioritize hygiene and proper technique.\n*   **Communication:**  Talk to your piercer about your concerns and preferences.  Don't be afraid to ask questions.\n*   **Pain:** Pain levels vary from person to person. Most people describe it as a quick, sharp pinch.\n*   **Healing time:** Septum piercings typically take 6-8 weeks to heal, but it can take longer for some individuals.\n*   **Aftercare:**  Following aftercare instructions is crucial to prevent infection and promote healing.  This usually involves cleaning the piercing twice a day with a saline solution.\n*   **Signs of infection:**  Be aware of the signs of infection, such as excessive redness, swelling, pain, pus, or fever.  If you suspect an infection, consult a doctor or your piercer immediately.\n\n**What to avoid:**\n\n*   **Getting pierced with a piercing gun:** Piercing guns are not sterile and can cause blunt force trauma to the tissue.\n*   **Touching the piercing with dirty hands.**\n*   **Using harsh cleaning products:** Avoid alcohol, hydrogen peroxide, and antibacterial soaps.\n*   **Changing the jewelry too soon:** Wait until the piercing is fully healed.\n*   **Playing with the jewelry:** Avoid twisting or moving the jewelry excessively.\n*   **Swimming in public pools or hot tubs during the healing process.**\n*   **Removing the jewelry:** Don't remove your jewelry during the healing process or the hole may close.\n\nBy choosing a reputable piercer and following proper aftercare, you can minimize the risks and ensure a successful septum piercing.\n",
